[[File:Alfred Lord Tennyson 1869.jpg|thumb|Alfred, Lord Tennyson]] "'''The Charge of the Light Brigade'''" is an [[1854 in poetry|1854]] [[narrative poem]] by [[Alfred, Lord Tennyson]] about the [[Charge of the Light Brigade]] at the [[Battle of Balaclava]] during the [[Crimean War]]. He wrote it on December 2, 1854, and it was published on December 9, 1854 in ''The Examiner''. He was the [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom]] at the time.
{{listen|filename=LightBrigade-Tennyson.ogg|title=The Charge of the Light Brigade|description=1890 recording by Alfred, Lord Tennyson on [[Edison cylinder|Edison wax cylinder]]}}
==History==
===Composition=== During the 1850s, when Great Britain was engaged in the [[Crimean War]], Tennyson wrote several patriotic poems under various pseudonyms. Scholars speculate that Tennyson created his pen names because these verses used a traditional structure Tennyson employed in his earlier career but suppressed during the 1840s,<ref>Francis 113</ref> worrying that poems like "The Charge of the Light Brigade" (which he initially signed only A.T.) "might prove not to be decorous for a poet laureate".<ref>Shannon and Ricks 3</ref>
The poem was written after the [[Light cavalry|Light Cavalry Brigade]] suffered great casualties in the [[Battle of Balaclava]]. Tennyson wrote the poem based on two articles published in ''[[The Times]]'': the first, published in November, 1854, provided the phrase "Some one has blunder'd" and thus the meter of the poem.<ref>Shannon and Ricks 1</ref> The poem was written in a few minutes on December 2 of the same year, based on a recollection of that account;<ref>Shannon and Ricks 2</ref> Tennyson wrote other similar poems, like "Riflemen, form in town and in Shrine" in a similar manner.<ref>Francis 115</ref>
===Later versions=== Tennyson made revisions to the poem due to criticisms by the American poet [[Frederick Goddard Tuckerman]] and others;<ref>Shannon and Ricks 7</ref> these were published in Tennyson's volume ''[[Maud and other poems|Maud and Other Poems]]''. These changes were criticized by several, including both Tennyson and Tuckerman.
Tennyson sent a version of the poem, after correcting the revisions in ''Maud'', at the soldiers' request.<ref name="Shannon and Ricks 10">Shannon and Ricks 10</ref> There, it was distributed in pamphlet form at the behest of [[Jane Griffin (Lady Franklin)|Jane, Lady Franklin]].<ref>Alfred Lord Tennyson, ''Poems'', ed. Hallam Lord Tennyson and annotated by Alfred Lord Tennyson (London: Macmillan, 1908), II, 369.</ref> The same version was used for the second printing of ''Maud''.<ref name="Shannon and Ricks 10"/>
Tennyson recited this poem onto a [[Phonograph cylinder|wax cylinder]] in 1890.
===Kipling's postscript=== [[Rudyard Kipling]] wrote "[[The Last of the Light Brigade]]" (1891) some 40 years after the appearance of "The Charge of the Light Brigade". His poem focuses on the terrible hardships faced in old age by veterans of the [[Crimean War]], as exemplified by the cavalry men of the Light Brigade. Its purpose was to shame the British public into offering financial assistance.<ref name="Hell Riders">{{Citation|last=Brighton|first=Terry|title=Hell Riders: The True Story of the Charge of the Light Brigade|url=http://www.terrybrighton.com/HR.htm|year=2005|publisher=Penguin|accessdate=}}</ref>
==Later references== {{in popular culture|date=November 2017}} [[File:Charge of the Light Brigade.jpg|thumb|A painting of the [[Charge of the Light Brigade]], the event that inspired the poem]] *The poem is referenced in Eugene V. Debs' [http://college.cengage.com/history/ayers_primary_sources/eugene_cantonspeech_1918.htm Canton Speech] (1918). *Lines from the poem are frequently referenced in ''[[To the Lighthouse]]'' by [[Virginia Woolf]], published in 1927. *The film ''[[The Bridge on the River Kwai]]'' (1957) features a quote from the poem, when United States Navy Commander Shears remarks on the guts of [[Colonel]] Nicholson, who stands to face the possibility of death for refusing that his officers participate in manual labor. *At the beginning of the horror film ''[[Burnt Offerings (film)|Burnt Offerings]]'' (1976), patriarch Ben prophetically foreshadows his family's destruction by paraphrasing, "Forward into the Valley of Death rode the six hundred." He says this for no apparent reason as his family first enters an isolated mansion in the country they intend to rent; none of them realize that the mansion is evil and requires periodic human sacrifice to renovate itself. * In the 1985 film ''[[Clue (film)|Clue]]'', Tim Curry states he is quoting Sir Alfred Lloyd Tennyson when he says "Ours is not to question why, ours is to do and die." * In the 1985 film ''[[The Falcon and the Snowman]]'', protagonist Chris Boyce recites several lines of the poem in response to insistent prompting by his father. * In 1990, a Season 1 episode of ''[[The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air]]'' entitled, "[[List of The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air episodes#Season 1 .281990.E2.80.931991.29|Def Poet's Society]]", features a poem based on The Charge of the Light Brigade. The sitcom's character, [[Joseph Marcell|Geoffrey]], impersonating a fictional famous poet named Raphael DeLaGhetto, recites a paraphrased version of the poem. Notably, he quotes, "CANNONS, TO THE LEFT OF THEM. CANNONS, TO THE RIGHT OF THEM. VOLLEYED AND THUNDERED". * In "[[Sacrifice of Angels]]", (''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'', Season 6 Episode 6, 1997), as the [[USS Defiant]] and a Federation fleet are about to go into battle against a much larger enemy force, [[Miles O'Brien (Star Trek)|Miles O'Brien]] and [[Julian Bashir]] recite lines from the poem until [[Nog (Star Trek)|Nog]] asks them to stop. Later in the episode [[Elim Garak]] asks how that poem ends, to be told by O'Brien "You don't want to know."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M1r9xljkCg0|title=Charge of the Light Brigade Deep Space Nine|first=|last=Zachary Burnett|date=6 March 2013|publisher=|accessdate=9 April 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref> *In the film ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]'' (1998), Private Reiben asks why eight men are sent to save one. Corporal Timothy E. Upham replies with a quote from the poem, "Theirs not to reason why, theirs but to do and die". Captain Miller responds that it is about their "duty as soldiers" to follow their orders, which supersedes everything, including their mothers, even if they think the mission is doomed to failure. Captain Miller shows his acquaintance with Emerson's works too. These foreshadow the later revelation that Captain Miller taught English composition at Thomas Alva Edison High School for eleven years before the war. *[[Jean Johnson (writer)|Jean Johnson]]'s military sci-fi book series, ''Theirs Not To Reason Why'', and the first book, ''A Soldier's Duty'', were nominated for the [[Philip K. Dick Award]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|website=Philip Dick Award|url=http://www.philipkdickaward.org/2012/01/index.html|title=2011 Awards|date=January 2012}}</ref> *In a response to the near destruction of Taffy 3 at the [[Battle of Leyte Gulf]], the padding in [[Admiral Nimitz]]'s inquiry about Halsey's Battleship Task Force, "Where is TF 34?" was "[[The world wonders]]." Some speculate that it is a reference to the poem and a comment on the heroic but near suicidal charge of the three [[destroyer]]s, four [[destroyer escort]]s, and lightly armed bombers and fighters of Taffy 3 against the Japanese Centre Force, made up of [[battleship]]s, including the ''[[Japanese battleship Yamato|Yamato]]'', heavy cruisers, light cruisers, and 11 destroyers.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hornfischer, James D. |title=Last Stand of the Tin Can Sailors}}</ref> * The poem inspired the [[Iron Maiden]] song "[[The Trooper]]" (1983).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ironmaidenbeer.com/aboutus#|title=Iron Maiden|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref> *The character Dr. Reed Akley on ''[[Manhattan (TV series)|Manhattan]]'' recites three lines of the poem, in Episode 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/cocktail-party-physics/2014/10/13/manhattan-recap-thin-man-implodes-spoilers/|work=Scientific American|title=Manh(a)ttan Recap: Thin Man Implodes|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref> *The TV show ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'' referenced the poem and its origins in series 21, episode 3, during a trip through Ukraine. When stopping at a spot near the battlefield, the team commented on the event and Richard Hammond quoted Tennyson's poem.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03wc9v7 |work=BBC2|title= Top Gear series 21, episode 3|date= February 16, 2014}}</ref> *[[Lamb of God (band)|Lamb Of God]] reference the poem in their 2009 album [[Wrath (Lamb of God album)|Wrath]]. In the song 'Contractor' the poem is paraphrased in the lines: "Ours is not to reason why; Ours is but to do if the pay rate's right." Making reference to a [[Nisour Square massacre|private military company involved in the Iraq War]]. *In the film ''[[The Blind Side (film)|The Blind Side]]'' (2009) Michael Oher doesn't know what to write about in his final English essay. His adoptive father quotes the first two stanzas and explains them using a football analogy.<ref>John Lee Hancock,'' [[The Blind Side (film)|The Blind Side]]''. 20 November 2009 (US)</re